{
  "text": "[11] We employed monthly mean precipitation data from the CMAP data set for [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The data were obtained from five kinds of satellite estimates (GOES precipitation index (GPI), outgoing-longwave-radiation-based precipitation index, Special Sensor Microwave Imager (SSM/I) scattering, SSM/I emission and microwave sounder unit values). This data set consists of pentad and monthly averaged precipitation rate values (mm/d) for the time period January 1979 to December 2001. The data have a 2.5\u00b0latitude by 2.5\u00b0longitude spatial resolution and global coverage. Though these data have a relatively short time history, their advances over other products are the global coverage, including land and oceanic/marine regions, and temporal resolution, that provides an opportunity to investigate intraseasonal fluctuations of precipitation along with its interannual variations. The CMAP data are believed to be among the most reliable data on precipitation. In comparisons with surface rain gauges, [CITATION_3] found root mean squared errors for 6 years of CMAP data of about 25% when considering grid points of 5 or more gauges. The data are available online at ftp://ftpprd.ncep.noaa.gov/pub/precip/ cmap.",
